<section xml:id="section-variables-and-evaluating-expressions">

    <title>Variables and Evaluating Expressions</title>

    <introduction>

        <objectives>
            <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
            <ul>
                <li><xref ref="mth60-evaluate-algebraic-expressions" /></li>
                <li><xref ref="mth60-distinguish-expressions-and-equations" /></li>
                <li><xref ref="mth60-evaluate-formulas" /></li>
                <li><xref ref="mth60-apply-perimeter-and-area-formulas" /></li>
                <li><xref ref="mth60-apply-volume-formulas" /></li>
                <li><xref ref="mth60-evaluate-other-geometric-formulas" /></li>
            </ul>
        </objectives>
        
        <p>A key sign that you are moving on from <em>arithmetic</em> to <em>algebra</em> is if you are using <term>variables</term>, discussed in this section. Any combination of numbers and variables using mathematical operations is called a mathematical <term>expression</term>. Some expressions are simple, and some are complicated. Some expressions are abstract, whereas some have context and meaning. The expression <m>\ell w</m> has two variables, and might represent the area of a rectangle of length <m>\ell</m> and width <m>w</m>. The expression <m>220 - a</m> has one variable, and is the expression for the maximum heart rate of a person who is <m>a</m> years old.</p>

        <p>Along with variables, and expressions, mathematical <term>equations</term> and <term>inequalities</term> are very important in algebra. In this section, we'll focus on expressions, and the remainder of this chapter is devoted to equations and iniequalities.</p>

