        <remark>
            <p>Note that unless an algebra problem specifies which letter(s) to use, we have a choice as to which letter we choose to represent our variable(s). However <em>without</em> any context to a problem, <m>x</m>, <m>y</m>, and <m>z</m> are the most common letters used as variables, and you may see these variables, especially <m>x</m>, a lot.</p>

            <p>Also note that the units we use are often determined indirectly by other quantitative information given in an algebra problem. For example, if we're told that a car has used so many gallons of gas after traveling so many miles, then it suggests we should measure gas mileage in <quantity><unit base="milepergallon" /></quantity>.</p>
        </remark>

    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Mathematical Expressions</title>
        <p>A mathematical <term>expression</term><index><main>expression</main></index> is any combination of variables and numbers using arithmetic operations. The following are all examples of mathematical expressions:<me>x+1\qquad 2\ell+2w\qquad\frac{\sqrt{x}}{y+1}\qquad nRT</me> Note that this definition of <q>mathematical expression</q> does <em>not</em> include anything with signs like these in them: <m>=</m>, <m>\lt</m>, <m>\leq</m>, etc.</p>

        <example xml:id="example-evaluate-temperature">
            <statement>
                <p>The expression: <me>\frac{5}{9}(F - 32)</me> can be used to convert from degrees Fahrenheit to degrees Celsius. To do this, we need a Fahrenheit temperature, <m>F</m>. Then we can <term>evaluate</term><index><main>evaluate</main></index> an expression is to replace its variables with specific numbers and calculate the result. In this case, we can replace <m>F</m> with a specific number.</p>

                <p>Let's convert the temperature <quantity><mag>89</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity> to the Celsius scale by evaluating the expression.<md>
                    <mrow>\frac{5}{9}(F - 32) \amp= \frac{5}{9}(\substitute{89} - 32)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{5}{9}(57)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{285}{9}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp\approx 31.67</mrow>
                </md></p>

                <p>This shows us that <quantity><mag>89</mag><unit base="fahrenheit" /></quantity> is equivalent to approximately <quantity><mag>31.67</mag><unit base="celsius" /></quantity>.</p>
            </statement>
        </example>

        <warning>
            <title>Vocabulary Usage</title>
            <p>The steps in <xref ref="example-evaluate-temperature">Example</xref> are not considered to be <q>solving an equation,</q> which is language you might be tempted to use. Instead, this process was <q>evaluating an expression.</q> There is a special algebra meaning for words like <q>solve</q> and <q>solution</q> that will come soon.</p>

            <p>In <xref ref="example-evaluate-temperature">Example</xref>, we <em>did</em> use equals signs, but that was so that we could assert that one expression equals another expression, which equals another expression, and so on. In the end, this example showed us that <m>\frac{5}{9}(F - 32)</m> <em>evaluates</em> to <m>\approx31.67</m> when <m>F</m> is <m>89</m>. It did not <q>solve</q> anything in a technical mathematical sense.</p>
        </warning>


