            <example>
                <title>Rising Rents</title>
                <statement>
                    <p>A model<fn><url href="https://www.rentjungle.com/average-rent-in-portland-or-rent-trends/"/></fn>  estimating the average rent of a one-bedroom apartment in Portland, Oregon, from January, 2011 to October, 2016, is given by<me>10.173x+974.78</me>where <m>x</m> is the number of months after January, 2011.</p>

                    <ol>
                        <li><p>According to this model, what was the average rent of a one-bedroom apartment in January, 2011?</p></li>
                        <li><p>If this model continues to be accurate, what will the average rent of a one-bedroom apartment be in January, 2020?</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <ol>
                        <li><p>This model uses <m>x</m> as the number of months after January, 2011, so to determine what it estimates the rent at in January, 2011, we will replace <m>x</m> with <m>0</m>:<md>
                            <mrow>10.173x+974.48 \amp=10.173(0)+974.48</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp \approx 974.48</mrow>
                        </md>According to this model, the average monthly rent for a one-bedroom apartment in Portland, Oregon, in January, 2011, was <m>\$974.78</m>.
                        </p></li>

                        <li><p>The date we are given is January, 2020, which is <m>9</m> years after January, 2011, or <m>72</m> months. We will replace <m>x</m> with <m>72</m>:<md>
                            <mrow>10.173x+974.48 \amp=10.173(72)+974.48</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp \approx 1706.94</mrow>
                        </md>According to this model, the average monthly rent for a one-bedroom apartment in Portland, Oregon, will be <m>\$1706.94</m> in January 2020.
                        </p></li>
                    </ol>
                </solution>
            </example>

