    <subsection>
        <title>Evaluating Expressions with Exponents, Absolute Value, and Radicals</title>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>The volume <m>V</m> of a cylinder with height <m>h</m> and radius <m>r</m> is given by <m>V=\pi r^2h</m>. Assume that a can of tuna has a radius of <quantity><mag>4</mag><unit prefix="centi" base="meter"/></quantity> and a height of <quantity><mag>2</mag><unit prefix="centi" base="meter"/></quantity>.<ol>
                    <li><p>Calculate the volume of this can in terms of <m>\pi</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Calculate the volume of this can and round the answer to two decimal places. Use the <m>\pi</m> button on your calculator, or assume <m>\pi\approx3.1415927</m>.</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol>
                    <li><p>Substitute <m>r=4</m> and <m>h=2</m> into the formula <m>V=\pi r^2h</m>, we have:<md>
                            <mrow>V \amp=\pi r^2h</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\pi (4)^2(2)</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\pi(16)(2)</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=32\pi</mrow>
                        </md>The volume of this can is <quantity><mag>32\pi</mag><unit prefix="centi" base="meter" exp="3"/></quantity>
                    </p></li>
                    <li><p>For this part, we substitute <m>\pi\approx3.1415927</m> into the first part's result, <m>32\pi</m>, and we have:<md>
                            <mrow>V\amp=32\pi</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp\approx 32(3.1415927)</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp\approx 100.53</mrow>
                        </md>The volume of this can is about <quantity><mag>100.53</mag><unit prefix="centi" base="meter" exp="3"/></quantity>.
                    </p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>The speed of a tsunami (in meters per second) can be modeled by:<me>\sqrt{9.8d}</me>where <m>d</m> is the depth of the tsunami (in meters). Determine the speed of a tsunami that has a depth of <quantity><mag>30</mag><unit base="meter"/></quantity>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Using <m>d=30</m>, we find:<md>
                    <mrow>\sqrt{9.8d} \amp= \sqrt{9.8(30)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{294}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp\approx 17.15</mrow>
                </md>The speed of tsunami with a depth of <quantity><mag>30</mag><unit base="meter"/></quantity> is about <quantity><mag>17.15</mag><unit base="meter" /><per base="second" /></quantity>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>


