    <subsection>
        <title>Evaluating Expressions with Negative Numbers</title>

        <p>When we substitute negative numbers into an expression, it's critical that we use parentheses around them. Let's look at some examples.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Evaluate <m>x^2</m> if <m>x=-2</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                    <mrow>x^2\amp=(-2)^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=4</mrow>
                </md>If we don't use parentheses, we would have:<md>
                    <mrow>x^2\amp=-2^2\amp\text{incorrect!}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-4</mrow>
                </md>Note that <m>-2^2=-4</m> because exponent has higher precedence over multiplication, while <m>(-2)^2=4</m> because parenthses have higher precedence over exponents.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Evaluate and simplify the following expressions for <m>x=-5</m> and <m>y=-2</m>:<ol>
                    <li><p><m>x^3y^2</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>(-2x)^3</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>-3x^2y</m></p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution><p>
                <ol>
                    <li><p><md>
                        <mrow>x^3y^2 \amp= (-5)^3(-2)^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=(-125)(4)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-600</mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                    <li><p><md>
                        <mrow>(-2x)^3\amp= (-2(-5))^3</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=(10)^3</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=1000</mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                    <li><p><md>
                        <mrow>-3x^2y\amp=-3(-5)^2(-2)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-3(25)(-2)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=150</mrow>
                    </md></p></li>
                </ol>
            </p></solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

